06331nam a22007215i 9780822383376DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20022002ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223833767 a10.1515/97808223833762doi  a(DE-B1597)553276  a(OCoLC)213455207  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aMUS0350002bisacsh04a781.6622100aRock Over the Edge :bTransformations in Popular Music Culture /ced. by Denise Fulbrook, Ben Saunders, Roger Beebe. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2002] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (399 p.) :b8 b&w photos, 2 tables, 1 figure  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- tDISCOURSES / HISTORIES -- tReflections of a Disappointed Popular Music Scholar -- tElvis Everywhere: Musicology and Popular Music Studies at the Twilight of the Canon -- t‘‘Think about What You’re Trying to Do to Me’’: Rock Historiography and the Construction of a Raced-Based Dialectic -- tHijacked Hits and Antic Authenticity: Cover Songs, Race, and Postwar Marketing -- tNEW SPACES / NEW MAPS -- tWhy Isn’t Country Music ‘‘Youth’’ Culture? -- tJust a Girl? Rock Music, Feminism, and the Cultural Construction of Female Youth -- tSatellite Rhythms: Channel V, Asian Music Videos, and Transnational Gender -- tThe ‘‘Feminization’’ of Rock -- tRock’s Reconquista -- tDESIRES / AFFECTS -- tA Fan’s Notes: Identification, Desire, and the Haunted Sound Barrier -- tMourning Becomes . . . ? Kurt Cobain, Tupac Shakur, and the ‘‘Waning of A√ect’’ -- tD.C. Punk and the Production of Authenticity -- tQueen Theory: Notes on the Pet Shop Boys -- tIndex -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis collection brings new voices and new perspectives to the study of popular—and particularly rock—music. Focusing on a variety of artists and music forms, Rock Over the Edge asks what happens to rock criticism when rock is no longer a coherent concept. To work toward an answer, contributors investigate previously neglected genres and styles, such as “lo fi,” alternative country, and “rock en español,” while offering a fresh look at such familiar figures as Elvis Presley, the Beatles, and Kurt Cobain.Bridging the disciplines of musicology and cultural studies, the collection has two primary goals: to seek out a language for talking about music culture and to look at the relationship of music to culture in general. The editors’ introduction provides a backward glance at recent rock criticism and also looks to the future of the rapidly expanding discipline of popular music studies. Taking seriously the implications of critical theory for the study of non-literary aesthetic endeavors, the volume also addresses such issues as the affective power of popular music and the psychic construction of fandom.Rock Over the Edge will appeal to scholars and students in popular music studies and American Studies as well as general readers interested in popular music.Contributors. Ian Balfour, Roger Beebe, Michael Coyle, Robert Fink, Denise Fulbrook, Tony Grajeda, Lawrence Grossberg, Trent Hill, Josh Kun, Jason Middleton, Lisa Ann Parks, Ben Saunders, John J. Sheinbaum, Gayle Wald, Warren Zanes  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aRock musicxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Rock.2bisacsh1 aBalfour, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeebe, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeebe, Roger, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCoyle, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFink, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFulbr